<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;chapmand&#64;pilot&#46;msu&#46;edu">hoshisabi</a> at September 13, 2004 10:55 AM</strong></p>
<p>Well, I can agree with some of the words but not others.</p>

<p>Mudflation describes a very specific thing.  It's not about progress it's about a game's age.  As new things get added the old things lose value.  It's not just items, although that's what it usually gets applied to, it's also about areas.  As a mud aged, new areas would get added which would either be ignored or they would replace existing areas.  How many people are in Sebilis anymore?  That's a very valid term.  When OoW comes out no one will be surprised to see some areas ignored.</p>

<p>Class balance:  You describe balancing classes for power but just about everyone agrees with one aspect of balance that has always been desirable.  The ability to sit down and actually play the game.  To this day I will never manage to make a character which gets as many invites to group as my piddly little cleric.  I have a partially time geared wizard that gets occasional invites, but my cleric can (and has been) AFK in the bazaar in trader mode and get multiple invites to group.  We all want a piece of that aspect of balance.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;loral&#64;loralciriclight&#46;com">Loral</a> at September 13, 2004 11:09 AM</strong></p>
<p>Thank you for the comment, Wyldrose.  You and I seem to agree on most everything except the conclusion.  Words that bring powerful yet different images to each of us do little good in helping us communicate.  I picked some of these words, specifically mudflation and timesink, because they are charged with emotion yet lacking in specific meaning.  We might as well replace them with "things I don't like".  </p>

<p>Uber and Casual are dangerous to the game.  They try to take five hundred thousand players and articulate them into two groups.  New features are sold as "casual friendly" when it really means its for low-level folks.  I don't like the term Casual at all.  Instead I prefer to talk about people with limited play time, people of lower levels, single-group hunters, or pickup raiders.  Even these tend to overgeneralize.</p>

<p>Some of these words, like Mudflation, Timesink, and Class Balance are simply annoying.  Others like Casual could steer the game in the wrong direction.</p>

<p>Everquest has no lack of players willing to communicate but many of these players lack the tools to communicate effectivly.  Throwing out these general and meaningless words and speaking in detail helps players steer the game in the right direction.</p>

<p>Meaningless metaphors and phrases plague modern writing.  Orwell pointed this out in 1945 and its just as true today.  You find these terms everywhere and Everquest is no different.</p>

<p>I don't wish to pick at what people say and I don't wish to drive them apart.  I wish for people to speak in details instead of broad generalities.  I want to see people speak with facts instead of emotions.  Let our emotions manifest themselves when we battle the Muramites!</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://www.celestialrising.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=146">feday</a> at September 13, 2004 11:38 AM</strong></p>
<p>The problems with these terms are emotions and opinions. Since these terms do not appear in any dictionary (as far as I could find) there is not set definition for them. The logical conclusion can only be that everyone thinks these terms convey a different message, leading to confusion.</p>

<p>On the whole I agree with Loral that terms should be used less, and that clarity helps us all in the end. On the other hand I agree with Wyldrose that telling people to not use these terms like 'uber' is just not feasible in the 'real world' (norrath) because they have been use for so long, and are integrated into the community so deeply.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;loral&#64;loralciriclight&#46;com">Loral</a> at September 13, 2004 11:42 AM</strong></p>
<p>Thank you, hoshisabi.  You bring up a couple of interesting thoughts.</p>

<p>Your definition of Mudflation supports a lot of what I say.  You bring up details of the term that are often lost on people who use it.  As new zones and new content get added, people don't use the old zones as much.  That itself is an interesting debate.  It is certainly true, but what damage does it cause?  Few think of that as mudflation though.  Many use Mudflation to talk about the dropping prices of bazaar loot or the increased power of high-level players.  Either way, it means many different things to many different people.</p>

<p>Your discussion of class balance is also interesting when you dig into the details.  I played a cleric for the last five years and also had few problems getting into a group, but recently I find that the groups I get in to would be better off with a druid.  My healing ability isn't required for LDON normals and Druid DPS is far superior.  Much of this is due to player perception, not the specifics of the classes.  Again, this is an excellent topic that is not represented well by the generic term "class balance".</p>

<p>Thanks, Feday.  It was never really my intent to see these words disappear.  You're right, they won't.  What I do hope is that some people will see the confusion and obfuscation (Thanks Azile!) that these generic terms create and begin to speak in more detail about what they actually mean.</p>
