<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Leoden at September 13, 2004 02:16 PM</strong></p>
<p>It's fnny how people can almost completely miss the point. Loral isn't saying stop using these words EVERYWHERE, but rather, when discussing something on boards or with devs, don't use game-speak or these overused terms; what seems plain and obvious to you by using these words, may not be plain to others, and in fact, others may think those terms mean something somewhat or completely different.</p>

<p>As Loral implied, get to the point! And don't use emotionally charged words to do it. Keep It Simple should be your guiding principle when posting. Instead of talking about "stupid timesinks", say "I don't think there are enough ways to increase faction with Chardok" or "There should be other ways to progress in the game for PoP flagging", etc. Say what you mean.</p>

<p>A statement like "EQ is falling prey to mudflation" is a practically meaningless statement because mudflation means so many different things to so many different people. You may as well have said "EQ is falling prey to calcifitoriosis." That statement will help get your TRUE point across to almost as many people (and by that I mean: not many) and be just as useless in the exchange of ideas.</p>

<p>Instead, say something like "Sony is putting items in the game that are so powerful, they are going to have even more difficulty in their attempt to balance the classes against each other and against mobs, not to mention not having much room for improved items in future expansions."</p>

<p>That is a much more informative statement with much less confusion as to what you meant. And see? What I think of as mudflation may be different from what you think of as mudflation. Q.E.D.</p>

<p>p.s. I made up calcifitoriosis, so it may or may not actually be a word. But then again, that's the whole point isn't it.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Teremar at September 13, 2004 03:45 PM</strong></p>
<p>Frankly I think you're being a bit obtuse on some of these, particularly class balance. Most people involved in those discussions know pretty well what others mean by those terms.</p>

<p>But I'll overlook that because I heartily agree with you that "casual" is far too loosely defined and that sloppiness is doing serious harm to the game. Less by the players (the term has been all but banished from The Runes, for instance) than by SOE staff. Here are some definitions of casual players I've seen:</p>

<p>1) People who do not raid frequently with a guild organized primarily for raiding (i.e. not a "family" guild).</p>

<p>2) People who raid very rarely or not at all.</p>

<p>3) People who do not play in long sessions.</p>

<p>4) People who do not spend a lot of time playing the game.</p>

<p>5) People who are not particularly interested in increasing the power of their character.</p>

<p>There are a few others I've seen, but don't think deserve serious consideration.</p>

<p>SOE has been guilty of assuming that people who meet one of these definitions meet all of them. Absor was (is?) particularly bad about this: some of the quotes where he essentially says that if  you don't raid you shouldn't care about your gear or having all your spells should be studied by business students world-wide as an example of how NOT to talk to your customers.</p>

<p>But I think SOE may be waking up to the fact that people who meet definition #1 don't necessarily meet definition #5. In fact as far as I can tell very few people who meet #5 are still playing the game (which makes Absor's statements all the more ironic).</p>

<p>Basically, progression is what EQ is all about at this point. If people can't progress they will quit. Heck, even if they see that at some point in the near future they will no longer be able to progress they'll go ahead and quit now. We need to move beyond "uber vs. casual" or even "raider vs. non-raider" (even though that's a huge improvement) and make sure all the various subpopulations that enjoy EQ can continue to progress.</p>

<p>And yes, the first step is to realistically identify who they are and get beyond lumping most of them together as "casuals."</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://www.cesspit.net/" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=151">Abalieno</a> at September 13, 2004 05:05 PM</strong></p>
<p>My idea of timesink:</p>

<p>A "timesink" is directly connected to the fun in a game. A personal, subjective concept but that can be transformed into something objective.</p>

<p>Basically a timesink is a part of the game that isn't really present. It's a "hole" in the fabric of the game. A timesink could be the travel time when during the travel nothing really happens. Or a player waiting a bar to fill.</p>

<p>Often a "timkesink" is compared to the repetition and this fits my model. Repetition is a strategy in the design to "fill" a space (in the gameplay) that isn't being actually developed.</p>

<p>A "timesink" is exactly a design strategy that replaces the void left by the gameplay with a time-sink. What should have been covered with gameplay is now hidden by an expense of time or a repetition of an action.</p>

<p>And the repetition is the link to the fun. Because the fun directly depends on what is felt "new".</p>
