<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://claws.guildportal.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=157">Talaen</a> at September 14, 2004 08:50 AM</strong></p>
<p>I think the distinction between casual and non-casual gamers is something that merits quite a bit more discussion, and really something that SOE needs to get a handle on if they want to seriously move forward with the game.</p>

<p>In my view, there are several different areas that all work together to determine how someone plays the game:</p>

<p>- Time to play.  Some people can play for 80+ hours every week, others for only a few on specific days.</p>

<p>- Ambition.  Some people are driven to progress their character and obtain new items, spells, levels, and so on - and others are not so driven and are just out there having fun.</p>

<p>- Immersion.  Many people see the game as nothing more than a hack-and-slash fest with a chatroom.  This is why we see silly character names and conversations in game.  Many others are deeply interested in the integrity of the game "world" itself.</p>

<p>- Activities.  Some people like raids, some people don't.  Some people like outdoor zones and others prefer dungeons.</p>

<p>- Challenge.  A great many players are content with very little in the way of challenge - other players completely thrive on it and grow bored quickly if not presented with insanely difficult areas to conquer.</p>

<p>You can't define "casual" gamers based on any one area - to do so ignores a lot of other things that factor into someone's enjoyment of the game.  I know many players and no two of them are exactly alike in how they approach the game.  Some have lots of time but little ambition, others have lots of ambition but really don't care about the story, and others still have moderate amounts of time, but hate to raid and constantly seek out the most challenging things they can do.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://claws.guildportal.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=158">Talaen</a> at September 14, 2004 09:11 AM</strong></p>
<p>I have to also disagree on the term "mudflation".</p>

<p>I spent a few years writing for MUDs and they suffered the same problem that everquest does - an inflationary cycle of player power and creature/item power that occurs as new content is added to the game.</p>

<p>Most people think of progression, or expansion of the game as the game having more to do.  New places to go and explore, new things to fight and conquer, and new treasures to find and use.  It goes without saying that in a level-based game these items and places will have to be more powerful than existing ones in order to entice players to use them.</p>

<p>The cycle is this - the original game is more or less balanced for players of all levels.  The game expands, and more challenging areas are added.  Encounters become tougher.  To compensate, players are granted more power in order to lower the difficulty of these encounters.  This is a normal, healthy cycle for any online game.</p>

<p>Mudflation is an ambiguous term.  It can refer to the cycle of expansion and progression, or more commonly it refers to a power bleed effect.  It's a given that expanding content will trivialize older content for a percentage of the player base.  That's expected - after all, that's why the new content was added.  The folks at the top will go do the new stuff, and the old stuff won't really challenge them anymore.  However, mudflation occurs when the additional power given to the players in the new content gets used by lower-level players in lower-level areas.  The best way to recognize mudflation is to look at the impact on the parts of the game that were not actually expanded.  For example, if all of the new content you added to the game was for levels 40 and above, yet suddenly, your level 20 characters are having a much essier time of things - you have mudflation.</p>

<p>Everquest is not alone in this problem.  Most online games have struggled with it and very few have overcome it.  In my experience, there is only one way to really prevent this from occurring and that is to be extremely strict when it comes to itemization and new content.  If you add a new level 30 dungeon, then it needs to be no more or less challenging than any other level 30 dungeon.  The weapons you add to that dungeon need to be equivalent in power to the weapons in other level 30 dungeons, and just as difficult to obtain.  This is a challenge for most area designers, as they are trying to come up with things that would entice players to try out the new area.</p>

<p>If you have a game with a history of this problem, the only way to really address the existing damage is quite simply to rewrite the older areas of your game.  The balance of things can be restored if you recognize that you have significantly raised the bar on player power.  Old areas will have to be redone, old items will have to be upgraded and replaced to correspond to the new "standard" of player power at all levels of the game.  For a pay-for-play game like Everquest, this is something that players will appreciate, but that won't really earn the company any more money in the short-term.  Long-term, it creates a healthier game which retains players, but I can count on one hand the number of business and marketing executives I've met who would really understand the importance of something like that.</p>

<p>Over the years the various members of the EQ Live team have all struggled with this, and they've made some visible attempts to try and rein things in - I think we can all agree that the recommended and required levels on items were a good step.  Unfortunately, they didn't do enough to stop this early on, and as a result there's a lot of content in the game which is simply not used even though there are still players to use it.  While it remains to be seen how much worse this gets, in my opinion there's already a very large "cleanup" project that should be done.<br />
</p>
