<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a href="mailto&#58;cdschmidt&#64;comcast&#46;net">Fanghawk</a> at September 14, 2004 11:33 AM</strong></p>
<p>I have to agree with Loral's premise.  Different words, as has been made explicitly clear just in response to this thread, mean different things to different people.  Among friends it's one thing to use jargon, with the developers, etc. it's another thing entirely.  For example, I very much want to level, and progress, and see high end zones, and have cool equipment.  I get to play about 10 hours a week but have real difficulty finding groups that are my level that want what I want.  Even my friends are less interested in progressing and more interested in tradeskills, and socializing than ever raiding.  If I want SOE to address my concerns, that is entirely different than what may concern my friends, yet we would both be labeled "casual" and I...who wish beyond all reasonable hope that I'll reach the high end (over 55) content some day, somehow, will never have my issues addressed under the "casual" umbrella.  That became painfully clear reading transcripts from the guild forums that SOE sponsored not too far back.  People raised issues for "casual" gamers several times, but generally they all meant different things, and they all wanted something different than I want. I'm sure there are many, many others who feel as I do but unless we specifically address our issues rather than whining about "casual" content, we'll never get heard.</p>
