<p>I'm deeply disappointed. SWG had tasks which might be to deliver a package, make something, kill this many mobs (wasn't easy but it was quite doable to my untwinked wookie), and all along the way if i had to log out to deal with real life, I could. The everquest team completely fumbled the ball for the people they claim comprise the majority of players (under 65) with their task system, despite  every promise they made. Maybe they think "casual" means "don't care" and maybe we neeed to communicate with them forcibly that time limited doesn't mean uninterested. </p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://claws.guildportal.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=171">Talaen</a> at September 15, 2004 10:47 AM</strong></p>
<p>I guess success or failure of the task system as a whole depends on what the objective of the system was.  I am mostly enjoying the task system for the following reasons:</p>

<p>1.  It gives better exp than I can normally get solo, plus better platinum than i get from the typical ldon split.<br />
2.  Every time I take a task, I end up running into two or three other players also working on their tasks and we form a group to help each other finish.  I meet new people this way AND get the tasks done.<br />
3.  I don't have to worry about the task expiring or anything - if i have to log out, or if something else comes up like a guildie needing a rez, then i can stop and come back to the task later.<br />
4.  The longest it's taken us so far to complete a group full of tasks is about 2 hours - not much longer than a single ldon can take counting time to get the group together, time to buff, and time to do the adventure.</p>

<p>The way I see it, tasks are great for when you don't have a group ready to go or can't find one.  There are a lot of times when i find myself sitting lfg at any one of the wayfarer camps, or trying to find a cleric or something to start a group.  Now, I can just go get a task, head out, and along the way meet up with a couple of folks and duo or trio our way through the tasks - we could never complete an LDoN like that.</p>

<p>I consider tasks a success in that they add something interesting to the game, and they are encouraging people to group and meet new people, but not requiring large, well-balanced groups like LDoNs do.</p>

<p>However, if their intent was to add solo content for players, then in this they have failed.  The only people who can really solo tasks are people who were soloing in dungeon areas before.  If you're a class that's traditionally group-dependant, like say a rogue, then you won't be able to complete many tasks on your own.<br />
</p>
