<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://claws.guildportal.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=175">Talaen</a> at September 15, 2004 03:33 PM</strong></p>
<p>I agree that Class Balance is something that's important to the health of the game.  I can understand Loral's point of view - a lot of times people use the term simply because they feel like their class isn't powerful enough, or can't do something it should.  That's not really what it's supposed to mean though.</p>

<p>Class Balance means that while classes should be relatively unique, each one should have a place in a group and be equally preferred.  Right now, the biggest problem is with the second part of that statement.  EQ has never succeeded in getting away from the "holy triumvirate" of cleric, warrior, and enchanter for many encounters, especially higher-end encounters.</p>

<p>People can argue endlessly all day long about what should or shouldn't be done to improve things, but to my mind the only way to fix it is really to concentrate on the areas in which the game needs improvement.</p>

<p>I will go on record right now as saying that my primary character is a paladin and as far as our role in groups goes, I think my class is perfectly fine.  Sure, I'd like to see my damage output go up some, because while i can take the hits i don't do much damage, but that doesn't mean my class isn't balanced.</p>

<p>If the devs were to work on ONE THING related to class balance, I would hope that it was the cleric requirement.  No offense to clerics, I have a 52 cleric myself and I love him, but it is simply wrong that one class should be considered required for so much of the game's content.  And while it's true that I can do a lot of things with a druid or shaman healing, assuming they're on the ball, there are still way too many things that we simply can not do without a cleric in the single-group game.</p>
