<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://www.yo.com" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=182">Candymang</a> at September 16, 2004 02:42 PM</strong></p>
<p>I will have to disagree with a couple of the top five most over-used and misunderstood terms that you listed. Here are a couple terms that I see all the time, and a summary definition of them.</p>

<p><br />
leet or l33t (n). A bastardization of the word "elite" in "hacker speak". Similiar to "uber", it is not quite the same thing but often can go hand-in-hand. While uber is best used to describe and item or anything else tangible (ex an uber breastplate), l33t is more apt to describe something intangible such as skill, knowledge, etc. Of course, sometimes they are mistakenly inter-changed since often people that have the most skill are able to acquire the best equipment, and vice-versa people with the best equipment have the most leverage to display their abilities. Of course, this touches upon the entire class balance issue, because a melee class that is l33t but not uber won't do you much good in a tough zone/encounter, and as much can be said about a cleric or enchanter that is uber but not l33t. For example, I can take the most talented warrior with 5 kazillion AA but is only ldon and EP geared and he will get owned in Ikkinz. On the hand, I myself as a cleric that is ldon/minor time/KT geared have been able to pull out wins that would have been CRs for some a$$-clown cleric that has rode his guild's coat-tails and is Time+ geared.</p>

<p><br />
Zerg (n). Zerging can mean a lot of different things as well. Zerging can be a strategy for a particular encounter, or it can be an entire raid philosophy, or it can simply mean max-dps at a certain time in any given fight. Allow me to clarify: Corinav, the "boss" fight in Plane of Water, is a zerg fight. Once he becomes targetable, the entire raid goes maximum dps to drop him before the timer for the event boots you out. Some guilds, however, use the zerg mentality for every fight. Taking 150+ people to Terris Thule and just throwing people at her with minimal strategy and crushing the encounter with pure numbers when the event could be done with a very skilled and tight raid of 35 people is the most popular, and negative, conotation of the term zerg. It's the reason that GoD in my mind  has so many instanced events that only allow set numbers of people to join in order to progress. Zerging is also used to denote the point in the fight at which all damage classes are supposed to use all of their damage disc and casters fire off their nukes in order to effectively "burn" a target down.</p>

<p><br />
Own or pwn (v). To own, or the hacker bastardization "pwn", is to display obvious dominance over someone/something else. A player can "pwn" another player in terms of gear/AA/etc, or could simply be able to display dominance in a duel format. While your 72-man Time-geared raid could walk into Vex Thal and "pwn" the entire place quite easily, they in turn would probably be "pwned" trying to walk into Txevu without massive planning and leadership to guide them through. </p>
